I think a lot about millennials who were the last generation able to create connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during an age of media gold, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without worrying about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without reason to question the pedestal we placed them on, parasocial relationships became foundations for our lives.
This is why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
This was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specific closed-off spaces.
Unconsciously, we die to be connected to the universal community that surrounded everything.
This is why so many people obsessively watch shows like The Office or movies like Anchorman, with lots of short references, much like memes.
We repeated these refs, knowing that most people were familiar with them.
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
there are too many things to see and no way to rationalize everything... will we escape hyper-saturation?
we get caught up in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatical figure.
we are forced to deal with a situation where we hold onto nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we enter parasocial relationships with more attention.
One understands that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without trampling on others along the way.
Without collective consciousness on media, we have developed class consciousness which helps us stay critical.
Some of us continue to place people on pedestals, only to be shocked when they fall off.
We are in a turbulent period and I can't wait to see where it will take us.
